    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup for **Ghost Ride the WHIP** is anchored by a high-upside outfield stack against favorable pitching. **Mickey Moniak** leads the squad with an elite 75.75 efficiency score, bolstered by a juicy matchup against Sasaki and a massive 14% park boost. Joining him, **Corbin Carroll** (72.32) and **Tyler Soderstrom** (70.03) provide significant pop. **Corbin Carroll** remains a priority start despite Gausman\u2019s presence, as his internal plate metrics and dynamic platoon advantage outweigh the SP threat. Meanwhile, **Max Muncy** (68.95) and **James Wood** (68.56) round out a formidable core; **James Wood** specifically benefits from an elite 10% order bonus as the lead-off hitter, successfully mitigating the risk of facing the southpaw Ray.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Alex Freeland**, who posted a respectable 53.65, narrowly missing the cut behind **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.63). While **Alex Freeland** offers a nice park factor, the proximity in scoring to **Vinnie Pasquantino** necessitated sticking with the established order of the latter, who maintains a slight edge in daily efficiency. We are closely monitoring the risk profile of **Trevor Story** (57.63), who remains in the starting lineup despite the presence of Valdez, because his profile thrives on \"slow delivery\" pitchers, providing us with a critical edge in our target category of stolen bases.\n\nWe are operating with caution regarding **Austin Riley** (56.88), who faces the toughest arm of the day in Painter. While **Austin Riley** avoids the \"Below Floor\" label, he is currently our most vulnerable asset; any further shift in his late-afternoon splits could see him sidelined in future iterations. **Luis Campusano** was an easy exclusion today with a score of 35.80, safely benched to preserve our limited game caps given his inability to clear the 40.0 efficiency threshold against Urena. We are effectively betting on **Mickey Moniak** and **Tyler Soderstrom** to provide the bulk of our categorical heavy lifting while banking on the speed-centric profiles of **Brice Turang** and **James Wood** to secure our SB floor.",
